        <h2 class="section-title">Trash compactors are mechanically simple. Most failures are one of four components — and we usually have the part on the van.</h2>

        <p>Trash compactors have fewer moving parts than almost any other kitchen appliance — a motor, a drive gear, a ram, a handful of switches, and a drawer. The failure mode list is short. The most common single reason a compactor "won't start" isn't a mechanical failure at all — it's the key switch sitting in the Off position, or the drawer not fully latched, or a circuit breaker that tripped. Our technicians check all of these before touching any components.</p>

        <p>KitchenAid and Whirlpool are the dominant brands in LA built-in kitchens, and we keep parts for both on the service vehicle. GE and Kenmore parts are sourced same-day. The average trash compactor repair in LA is a door switch, directional switch, or drive gear — all under $250 total — and takes less than an hour.</p>

        <!-- SELF-CHECK -->
