      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My trash compactor won't start — what should I check first?</h3>
        <p>Check: key switch in On position, door fully clicked shut, circuit breaker not tripped, hold Start button 2–3 full seconds. These four things solve 40% of "won't start" calls without any parts. If still nothing, call {phone}.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is it worth repairing a trash compactor?</h3>
        <p>Usually yes — most repairs are $150–$250 on units that cost $700–$1,200 to replace. Motor replacement ($200–$350) is still worth it in most cases. Control board failure on an older unit is the exception where replacement may make more sense — we'll tell you honestly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>The ram is stuck and won't move — what do I do?</h3>
        <p>Unplug the unit first. Look for a glass bottle, can, or folded cardboard jammed between the ram and the cabinet wall. Remove it carefully. Never pry a stuck ram — you'll damage the frame. If the path is clear and the ram still won't move, call us — it's the directional switch or drive gear.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

